Symbol	File Type	Description
d	directory	A file used to store other files.
-	regular file	Includes readable files, images files, binary files, and compressed files.
l	symbolic link	Points to another file.
s	socket	Allows for communication between processes.
p	pipe	Allows for communication between processes.
b	block file	Used to communicate with hardware.
c	character file	Used to communicate with hardware.

ls -lt /var/log  #Will sort the files by timestamp (t)
ls -l -S /var/log #Will sort the files by size (S)
ls -lSr /var/log #Will reverse the order of any sort (r)


su - #Allows you to temporarily act a different user
sudo #Allows you to execute a command as another user without create a new shell

Permissions
sysadmin@localhost:~/Documents$ ls -l hello.sh                                  
-rw-r--r-- 1 sysadmin sysadmin 647 Dec 20  2017 hello.sh 
#The first - tells us that this is a regular file
#The following rw- tells us the permission for the owner of the file which we can also see by the user owner field sysadmin
#The following r-- is set for the group who owns the file
#The following r-- is for everyone else that is not the owner or in the group
r  #allows for files to be read or copied
w  #Allows for contents to be modified or overwritten. Allows for files to be added or moved from a directory as well
x  #Allows for a file to be run as process although script files require read permission as well

Changing File Permissions
chmod #Is used to change the permissions of a file or directory

sysadmin@localhost:~/Documents$ ls -l hello.sh                                  
-rw-r--r-- 1 sysadmin sysadmin 647 Dec 20  2017 hello.sh   

#Below is the syntax to change permissions for either owner, group, others or all users
SET
u  #Is for the user who owns the file
g  #Is for the group who owns the file
o  #Is for the others not the owner or member of the group owner
a  #Refers to the user, group and others
ACTION
+  #Add the permission, if necessary
=  #Specifies the exact permission
-  #Removes the permission, if necessary
PERMISSIONS
r  #read
w  #write
x  #execute 

chmod [<SET><ACTION><PERMISSIONS>] FILE NAME

Changing File Ownership
sudo chown root hello.sh #Will change the owner from sysadmin to root

cat #Will display the entire contents of a file
head #Will display top of the file
tail #Will display the bottom of the file
head -n 5 alpha.txt  #Will display the first five lines of the text
tail -n 5 alpha.txt  #Will display the last five lines of the text


~/Documents$ mv people.csv Work  #Will move people.csv to Work
~/Documents$ mv numbers.txt letters.txt alpha.txt School #Moving all the files from Documents to School directory

Removing files
~/Documents$ rm linux.txt

ipconfig #Displays the network configuration
apt-get upgrade #Will updated all packages
apt-get purge #Will delete all of a package's file
